      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The argument that regulators will pick winners and losers is a classic defense used by big tech to avoid accountability, but it ignores the reality that the government already intervenes in markets through subsidies, tax breaks, and safety standards. True corruption arises when the regulated entities themselves lobby for rules that protect their specific interests, not when the government sets general rules for all businesses. Instead of a free-for-all where monopolies crush competition, we are moving toward a system where the market functions fairly, ensuring that innovation comes from merit rather than the ability to buy up every competitor.",
      "source": "target",
